1. Shared GPU Abstractions
Unified model interface – Each algorithm needs a GPU-native representation (weights, trees, centroids…) built around a common struct or vtable so the catalog and prediction APIs don’t care whether the model lives on CPU or GPU memory.
Execution context – Extend ml_gpu_context.c to manage per-model buffers, persistent device allocations, streams, and fallbacks. We’ll also need ref-counting/cleanup hooks when a model is dropped from the catalog.
2. Per-Algorithm GPU Implementations
For each algorithm (RF, decision tree, SVM, kNN, regression, clustering, etc.) we need:
Training kernels – e.g. RF tree growth, gradient descent loops, kNN indexing.
Inference kernels – evaluate a trained model entirely on device.
Serialization/deserialization – so GPU models can be stored in neurondb.ml_models and rehydrated without dropping to CPU.
Fallback path – enforce the rule: if neurondb.gpu_enabled and the required GPU kernel is available, run 100% on GPU; otherwise fall back to the existing CPU code.
Many algorithms in src/ml are still pure CPU; we’d be writing large amounts of CUDA/ROCm/Metal code and refactoring the CPU flow to call out to a GPU façade.
3. Backend-Specific Work
For every backend (CUDA, ROCm, Metal) we’d need equivalent kernel coverage. That’s tens of kernels per algorithm.
We also have to maintain feature parity: e.g. GPU logistic regression must support all regularization/cost options the CPU version does.
4. Integration with Unified API
neurondb_train, neurondb_predict, neurondb.evaluate, etc. must dispatch to GPU or CPU versions purely based on availability; no partial mixing.
Catalog metadata needs to track whether the stored model blob is GPU-specific or GPU/CPU convertible.
5. Testing & Tooling
Extensive regression tests comparing GPU vs CPU outputs.
Performance benchmarking harness to ensure GPU actually offers benefit.
GUC exposure to toggle kernels, select backends, and debug fallbacks.
